post_cb({"19584395": {"CommentCount": "7", "ViewCount": "127", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "671366", "CreationDate": "2013-10-25T08:05:47.293", "LastActivityDate": "2013-10-25T08:22:40.850", "Title": "How is this getting evaluated?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "19584496", "LastEditDate": "2013-10-25T08:13:44.580", "Id": "19584395", "Score": "4", "Body": "<p>I am feeling very stupid to asking this question. but cant figure out the reason on my own.</p>\n<pre><code>int main()\n{\n    int target;\n    int buffer =10;\n    const int source = 15;\n    target = (buffer+=source) = 20;\n    cout &lt;&lt; target+buffer;\n    return 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p><code>target = (buffer+=source) = 20;</code> will become <code>target = (25) = 20</code>.</p>\n<p>But if I am giving same statement in my source file, it is giving l-value error.</p>\n<p>How the value of <code>target+buffer</code> is printing 40.</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++>", "OwnerUserId": "1216931", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_19584395_19584496_0": {"section_id": 654, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "length": 11}}, "n3337": {"so_19584395_19584496_0": {"section_id": 644, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "length": 11}}, "n4659": {"so_19584395_19584496_0": {"section_id": 682, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "length": 11}}}, "19584496": {"ParentId": "19584395", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "3", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_19584395_19584496_0\">Some predefined operators, such as +=, require an operand to be an\n  lvalue when applied to basic types [\u00a713.5/7]</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><code>buffer+=source</code> returns a lvalue reference to <code>buffer</code>. <strong>So you have not compile error.</strong></p>\n<p>your statement <em>can</em> be evaluate as:</p>\n<pre><code>buffer+=source;\nbuffer=20;\ntarget=20;\n</code></pre>\n<p>But modifying <code>buffer</code> twice in a statement is <strong><em>undefined behavior</em></strong> and another compiler can evaluate something else as result. <em>(Not sure in this case also!)</em></p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "952747", "LastEditorUserId": "952747", "LastEditDate": "2013-10-25T08:21:55.917", "Id": "19584496", "Score": "5", "CreationDate": "2013-10-25T08:11:04.947", "LastActivityDate": "2013-10-25T08:21:55.917"}});